post_text:
What is GEAR UP? (Gaining Early Awareness and Readiness for Undergraduate Programs)
This is a federally-funded, statewide grant in Wyoming that provides services to 7th-12th grade, income-eligible students each year. The goal of GEAR UP is to increase the number of eligible students who are prepared to enter and succeed in post-secondary education.

WHAT WE DO:
Create Individual Academic Plans
Offer Tutoring services
ACT Prep
Help with financial aid and applying for scholarships
Explore different colleges and degrees
Organize Monthly Lunch Meetings
College visits and campus activities
Participate in Summer Academies (optional)
!!Scholarship Opportunities!!
and so much more!

Please contact Michelle Hale for an application or with any questions.
mhale@westernwyoming.edu
307-248-3254

** Income-Eligible students are those who qualify for free and reduced lunch

Today is the day - Don't forget!!
We would like to invite all incoming 7th graders and any new to SVMS 8th graders to our school on Aug. 18th to meet the teachers and get familiar with the school. Here are a few guidelines to help maintain a safe environment for you as you visit the school.
Please help us by following the guidelines below.

• Hours for the school visit are 2:00 pm – 6:00 pm on Aug. 18th.
• We would politely ask that only incoming 7th graders and new to SVMS 8th graders attend on this date to help keep our numbers manageable.
• We would ask that only one parent attend with the incoming student and refrain from bringing siblings into the building.
• We would ask that both parent and student wear a face covering while in the building.

We look forward to seeing all our students on Aug. 25 for the first day of school.

Attention 7th grade football:
Football gear will be handed out to 7th graders on Tuesday, August 18th, from 4-6pm on the SVMS mezzanine. This will be on a first-come, first-served basis. Please only have one parent come to the middle school with your child and both will need to be in a face covering. Each student as they come up to the mezzanine will need to use hand sanitizer on the way in and way out along with having a mask on. Please also remember they will need a physical before the first day of practice that was completed after May 1, 2020. If you cannot make this time for gear handout, it can also be done on the first day of school.

At this point, 8th grade gear for football will be handed out on the first day of practice, August 25th.

Please call (307) 886-4970 or email jeanderson@lcsd2.org, rpebbles@lcsd2.org with any questions you may have.

Middle School Volleyball open gym information:
If you are feeling ill, please do not come to open gym.
If you have been exposed to COVID-19 or are experiencing any symptoms please do not come to open gym.
Do not bring any of your own volleyballs.
Maintain social distancing guidelines at 6ft.
Each athletes temperature will be checked before they can participate
Each parent will have to sign a waiver form before their child can participate

Starting Tuesday June 23 and Thursday June 25th from 6:30pm- 8:00pm (then Tuesday’s and Thursdays after that, please check coaches schedule)

7th grade students or new 8th grade students will need a physical to participate in open gym and/or any upcoming volleyball camps. If you do not have a physical you will be unable to participate.

8th grade students physical from last year will work, but they will need a new physical before tryouts in August that was obtained after May 1st 2020.

Thank you for your patience, please send an email to kalin.schwab@lcsd2.org with any questions you may have.

Students and parents, SVMS will be open for end of year check out on the following days from 7:30 am to 4:00 pm- Tuesday May 26th, Wednesday May 27th, and Thursday May 28th. We will also be open on Friday May 29th from 7:30 am to 12:00 noon. Please stop by on one of those days to complete your end of year check out. This includes locker clean out, payment of any lunch balance, book check in, computer check in if you checked one out and to get your yearbook. Please be aware, we will be letting small groups in at a time and will be continuing social distancing practices. This could result in wait times.

Thank you,

Steve Burch Principal SVMS

Here are some detailed instructions on how to access the educational learning opportunities for your student. They are accessible on LCSD2’s website. Here’s the easiest way to find them.

Go to http://www.lcsd2.org/covid19/
Click on the blue “At Home Learning” button.
That screen will ONLY show the recent additions.
Click on “Secondary Education” towards the top right (black header bar with white writing).
This will pull up a list of ALL secondary resources.
SVMS resources are listed on the left-hand side by grade and subject.

Hopefully you’ll be able to access these and continue learning from home!

All meetings and events at SVMS are canceled until April 6th. Please review the following information from LCSD#2.

Message from LCSD#2:

Late this afternoon, Sunday, March 15, Governor Mark Gordon and State Superintendent Jillian Balow recommended that all schools are closed to students through at least April 3. LCSD#2 is following the recommendation of Governor Gordon and Supt. Balow and will close all schools until April 6. LCSD#2 Administration will release further plans after meetings are concluded Monday morning. Updates will be on our websites, social media and SVI.

post_text:
SVMS Parents
Here are some instructions and video links to our ebook collection for our required AR reading at the middle school

Step #1: go to the Star Valley Middle School website: https://svms.lcsd2.org
Step #2: click on the “LIBRARY” button (top-right)
Step #3: Under “Resources” click the “Gale Resources”
Step #4: Now click on the button “Middle School Resources” (top of page)
Step #5: Now click on the blue “GVRL” button (Middle School ebooks)
(it may ask for a password which is svlibrary or library)
Step #6: Now type in the book you are looking for in the search box (see below)
You may need to do an advanced search for the book then scroll down to publication title search
Step #7: When the book comes up, click the “view ebook” and begin reading

If you are having trouble finding your book, please watch the 2 YouTube videos
Thanks and enjoy your reading. Please call the middle school if you have any questions.

Basic Access
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8WMr-UBuMj4&t=5s
Trouble Shooting
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8_Zc3opJINg

post_text: Congratulations to Denise Frazier, LCSD#2 Teacher Of The Year!! Denise is an art teacher at Star Valley Middle School. She has been teaching in Star Valley for seven years. She said, "Art is about discovering and creating ingenious ways of problem solving, integrating principles, presenting information and being innovative. Art is about developing the whole brain, teaching tolerance, emotional intelligence, and resilience. These are all characteristics that research shows will help our students be successful in life."

Hello track parents. A couple of updates--for the meet this Friday in Evanston, it will start at 10am instead of 11am. Bring your umbrella, it may get wet. Also we have decided to go back to the Jackson meet which will be on May 2nd. We will not be attending the Rock Springs meet. The field events in Jackson start at noon and the running starts at 2pm. Our kids will be late because of WYTOPP, we are hoping to be there by 1:30pm.
We are so grateful for those who were able to help us out at our track meet. We had a great day and the weather was fantastic.

post_text: Friday April 12th was a rewarding day for the 7th and 8th grade Academic Bowl teams who traveled to Lyman to compete with students from 7 other schools around the area. Students from each school are divided into mixed teams representing all the schools involved, they then rotate through eight different rounds of 20 minutes each answering fast-paced questions about math, science, history, geography, English, and general knowledge. At the end of the day medals are awarded to the top three teams in each grade. Star Valley students brought home 5 medals and all had a great time being challenged and meeting fellow scholars.

Star Valley and Jackson 8th grade orchestra students pose for a picture with guest clinician Barb Scowcroft, Star Valley orchestra teacher Lisa Barber, and Jackson orchestra teacher Vince Gutwein. Fantastic opportunity for Star Valley students to interact with a professional conductor and performer and play in a world class venue at Walk Hall in Teton Village! Thanks to all the parents who drove up for the concert - as always Star Valley had great community support for the event!
You can learn about Barb Scowcroft at https://utahsymphony.org/bio/barbara-ann-scowcroft/
